node.text:
The boulders and routes of Little Cottonwood Canyon are what we consider our ‘home crag.’ They forge the character of our local climbing community. They are the connection between our historic legacy and the potential of our future climbing generations. This Friday, September 3rd, is the last chance we have to use our collective voice as a community to protect the climbing in Little Cottonwood Canyon. 
 
Under UDOTs plans for a gondola or additional lanes, over 100 iconic boulders will be impacted and the beauty of the canyon forever altered. The current views of pristine granite and pines is set to be interrupted by towers and cables; the rush of the river replaced with the consistent hum of machinery.

Less destructive options exist, such as UDOT's Enhanced Bus without Roadway Widening proposal.

Help us protect the bouldering in Salt Lake City. Transportation infrastructure that physically and permanently alters the canyon should only be considered after less impactful options have been implemented and shown not to be effective.

Take a moment to learn about the challenges and proposed solutions being considered here in Little Cottonwood Canyon, and comment to UDOT before the September 3rd, 2021 deadline.

Video: @jonvickersphoto

Patagonia may be known for its alpine routes, but the granite blocs scattered around El Chaltén and Torres del Paine National Park have caught the eye of many intrepid climbers. For BD Athlete Nalle Hukkataival (@nalle_hukkataival), the allure of the boulders was enticing enough to dedicate a trip to Patagonia to sample and explore the blocs below the walls.

#liveclimbrepeat 

Video: @lena_bam

We all have our best #beladies in our lives – the ones we can count on to be there, to inspire us, to push us. At Black Diamond, we’re constantly in awe of the number of bold, passionate women around us.
In honor of International Women's Day, tell us – who are your heroes? Use #beladies in your posts to be featured on our page. #internationalwomensday #liveclimbrepeat #liverunrepeat #liveskirepeat

node.text:
The timing was perfect: with the annual Kings and Queens of Corbet’s ready to take off, BD Athlete Parkin Costain (@parkincostain) set up shop for a week in Jackson Hole just as a classic Wyoming storm-cycle blanketed the hill with a few feet of fresh. With the unstable snowpack of the backcountry, Parkin decided to take advantage of the tram and go big on the 4,000-foot vertical runs that Jackson is famous for. You gotta get up to get down. 

#liveskirepeat
@blackdiamond_snow

Video by @benshicreative

"The pile of hardened gritstone blocks are scattered like a dump of washer-dryer combos at the base, and no number of big pads or the help of spotters can help you now. Elvis leg will be your death if you don’t attend to that little cobble, shiny and polished as a marble and half the size."

BD Ambassador @chris_schulte recently made a pilgrimage to explore “god’s own stone,” otherwise known as England’s famed and notorious gritstone. In his own words, everything you’ve heard about the “grit” is true … “except when it’s not.” 

Link in bio for more words by Schulte. #liveclimbrepeat

node.text:
In the fall of 2019, BD Athlete Joe Grant (@alpineworks) was invited to “The Land of Smiles” to experience first-hand the burgeoning Thai trail running community. This film and the accompanying essay by Joe (link in bio!), captures his lasting sentiment since leaving Thailand. As he puts it so eloquently, “the essential elements to a long and happy running life is the search for balance... While trail running is in its infancy in Thailand, they already have the right ingredients to be one step ahead.”

Link in bio for more.

#liverunrepeat

The boulders and routes of Little Cottonwood Canyon are what we consider our ‘home crag.’ They forge the character of our local climbing community. They are the connection between our historic legacy and the potential of our future climbing generations. This Friday, September 3rd, is the last chance we have to use our collective voice as a community to protect the climbing in Little Cottonwood Canyon. 
 
Under UDOTs plans for a gondola or additional lanes, over 100 iconic boulders will be impacted and the beauty of the canyon forever altered. The current views of pristine granite and pines is set to be interrupted by towers and cables; the rush of the river replaced with the consistent hum of machinery.

Less destructive options exist, such as UDOT's Enhanced Bus without Roadway Widening proposal.

Help us protect the bouldering in Salt Lake City. Transportation infrastructure that physically and permanently alters the canyon should only be considered after less impactful options have been implemented and shown not to be effective.

Take a moment to learn about the challenges and proposed solutions being considered here in Little Cottonwood Canyon, and comment to UDOT before the September 3rd, 2021 deadline.

BD Athlete Alex Honnold (@alexhonnold) doesn’t have to rely on much gear, but for all of his groundbreaking exploits on rock, there was always one crucial component: Chalk. That's why we created ECO Gold––the latest addition to our engineered chalk. 

It's made from pure magnesium carbonate, which is the byproduct of the desalination process as opposed to being mined from the earth like typical chalk. Plus, a portion of proceeds goes to support the @honnoldfoundation. 

Link in bio for more. 

#liveclimbrepeat
